Practice 2 - Fraud - Best model and Explainability¶

Here, in the last step of our Machine Learning model for fraud detection, is to improve our best models (in this case the XGBoost). After importing the selected libraries as well as the "selected" dataset, we will generate a grid with the main hiperparameters in order to find the best model. As a final step, we will study the explainability of the model with the SHAP library with the objetive to find which variables define more the final result in the model.

XGBoost Grid¶

To fit a training dataset using XGBoost, an initial prediction is made. Residuals are calculated based on the predicted value and the observed values. A decision tree is created with the residuals using a similarity score of the residuals. The similarity of the data of a leaf is calculated, as well as the similarity gain of the subsequent split. The gains are compared to determine an entity and a threshold for a node. The output value for each leaf is also calculated using the residuals. For classification, the values are generally calculated using log odds and odds ratios. The output of the tree becomes the new residual for the dataset, which is used to build another tree. This process is repeated until the residuals stop decreasing, or the specified number of times. Each subsequent tree learns from the previous trees and is not assigned the same weight, unlike how Random Forest works.

To use this model for prediction, the output of each tree multiplied by a learning rate is added to the initial prediction to arrive at a final value or classification.

In [5]:
params = {"subsample":[0.25,0.5, 0.75, 1], 
          "colsample_bytree":[0.25,0.5, 0.75, 1], 
          "max_depth":[2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 15, 20], 
          "min_child_weight":[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 10, 15, 20], 
          "learning_rate":[0.9,0.6,0.3, 0.1, 0.03, 0.01],
          "n_estimators":[100]
         }

Being "subsample" the ratio of the training instances, setting it to 0.5 means that XGBoost would randomly sample half of the training data prior to growing trees, preventing overfitting. Subsampling will occur once in every boosting iteration. Hence, we will set it between 0.25 and 1

For "colsample_bytree" the range selectes is from 0.25 to 1 due to it defines what percentage of features ( columns ) will be used for building each tree. The set of features for each tree is likely to be different, especially with a low number of features, therefore the range selected.

We also have set the "max depth" of the resulting tree from 2 to 20, with a "minimun child weight" from 1 to 20. For max depth, we set more lower numbers, due to trees with a high depth can tend to overfit. Similar as with minimun child weight, as we set firts from 1 to 5 and the 10, 15 and 20, as more child weight means a more complex model.

Finally, the learning rate we have set it to try values from 0.9 to 0.01 as is the shrinkage it does at every step. Finally we will run the XGBoost 100 times as the number of estimators is set to 100.

Model explainability¶

Model explainability refers to the concept of being able to understand the machine learning model. In order to do this we will do a global explainability looking at which.

Global explainability

In [11]:
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(best_xgb.best_estimator_)
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(xtest)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, xtest)

Being the variable type one in which we performed a mean enconding, we can conclude that those with 0 were "Cash-in", "debit" and "payment", and as we can see in the plot those tend to 0. The others,"Cash-out" and "Transfer", which had a fraud rate of 0.1547% and 0.6501% respectively tend to the final output to 1.

Old and new balance origin are the 2 and 3 respectively features that more affect to the final output for the old balance we can see that the gross low values tend to define the no fraud, meanwhile for the new balance origin, we can hint more high values in the left side of the graph, which means that it tends to mean not fraud.

More clear is for the amount. The majority of high values represent a not fraud. But we can see a bright red dot at the right of the map, that as we observed in the EDA, can be representative of those amounts closer to the 10 millions

One of the easier to analyze is the transactions per step variable in which the lowee the value the higher tend to fraud, being the more impactful for fraud cases as they can have an impact on the output up to 12.5.
